<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Observer: Not all bad
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Renault Vehicules Industriels, an arm of the French carmaker, has come up
with one of the less attractive examples of Franglais. Yesterday's interim
statement mentions the 1991 first half pre-tax losses of FFr128m 'apres
badwill'.
Badwill? Yes, says Renault cheerfully, it is the opposite of goodwill and,
rather than being a bad thing, is actually something of a windfall. It had
paid less than it expected to acquire full control (in 1990) of Mack Trucks
in the US, so le badwill is a pot of money that turned up because the
provisions made in advance of the acquisition were too generous.
Vive la difference.
