<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Policies 'promote business start-ups'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOTH THE UK and Germany have experienced substantial growth in
self-employment but the increase has been most dynamic in the UK, according
to a report from the Anglo-German Foundation for the Study of Industrial
Society, a charitable group.
In its report, the group, which seeks to promote closer understanding
between the UK and Germany, compares the phenomenon of self-employment in
both countries and examines common characteristics and differences.
The report says the economic and policy climate in the UK promotes business
start-ups, while the climate in Germany favours maintaining those who are
already self-employed.
The authors conclude that the increasing importance of self-employment in
the labour market indicates a growing need for policymakers to understand
the implications of self-employment for the labour market.
The report says: 'These questions are particularly relevant within the
context of the newly emerging market economies of eastern Europe - not least
in the former German Democratic Republic - where the development of
self-employment and entrepreneurship is frequently seen as a mechanism for
stimulating the transition to a market economy and for absorbing some of the
unemployment involved in such a transition.'
The report says that before the 1980s, commentators on the labour market
typically ignored self-employment as a transitory stage at best for emerging
enterprises towards becoming fully fledged small businesses.
Self-Employment in the UK and Germany. Anglo-German Foundation, 15 Albion
Close, Parkstone, Poole, Dorset BH12 3LL. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
