<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Complaint system in schools 'woeful'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ARRANGEMENTS for parents to make complaints about their children's
schools are 'woefully inadequate', the National Consumer Council says in a
report published today.
The council says that the Parent's Charter has done little to help parents
who want to complain - and the government's new white paper on opting out
might make it even harder for some.
The government-funded council calls for the existing 'bewildering array' of
formal and informal complaints systems to be replaced by a simple,
well-publicised system for complaints in every school and local education
authority.
Lady Wilcox, who chairs the council, said: 'The government takes the view
that it should be the job of the school governors to deal with complaints.
Our research shows that few governors are yet trained to handle complaints
and, so far, they tend not to override the decisions of the headteacher.'
The council says any new system should cover schools that have opted out of
local education authority control. Parents of children at such schools must
take up complaints with the Department for Education, 'which has a poor
track record of dealing with parents' complaints'.
It says pupils aged 16 and over should be allowed to use such a system. It
urges the government to find ways of helping younger children to complain.
The remit of the local-government ombudsman should be extended to cover
complaints about maladministration of internal school matters.
When things go wrong at school. National Consumer Council, 20 Grosvenor
Gardens, London SW1W 0DH. Pounds 2.50.
