<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Logica almost doubled at Pounds 7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOGICA, the computing services company, saw pre-tax profits almost double
last year as its troubled North American subsidiary returned to the black.
The shares rose 10p to close at 140p.
Profits before tax were Pounds 7.06m. Last time's Pounds 3.7m was struck
after restructuring costs of Pounds 6.4m. Sales were slightly higher at
Pounds 200.4m (Pounds 197.8).
Earnings per share were 7p, against losses of 1.6p after a higher tax charge
of Pounds 4.64m resulting from overseas losses. The proposed final dividend
is 2.5p making a total of 3.65p (3.5p) for the year.
Year-end cash balances stood at Pounds 13.7m, against Pounds 15m at the
beginning of the year.
The results have been depressed for the past two years by a combination of
the recession in the UK and steep losses in North America.
This year sales in the UK grew from Pounds 114m to Pounds 122m with profits
slipping from Pounds 8.8m to Pounds 7.1m. North American revenues slipped
from Pounds 26.3m to Pounds 23.8m, but the subsidiary ended up Pounds
550,000 in the black, compared with a loss of Pounds 2.7m.
The main reversal was in mainland Europe where profits of Pounds 2m last
year became a Pounds 1.7m loss as the German economy deteriorated.
Mr David Mann, Logica managing director, said he did not expect to see much
of a contribution to profits from mainland Europe or elsewhere outside the
UK in the coming year. Priority in North America was being given to
investment in marketing and sales. Exchange rate movements had contributed
nothing to the results.
COMMENT
Logica has put up a strong performance in its key market, the UK, in
atrocious conditions. The computing services sector is suffering unrelieved
gloom at present so analysts are taking a cautious view of Logica's
improvement. Nevertheless, the management's decision to cut hard and deep
last year has been vindicated and the North American black hole has been
plugged. Pre-tax profits of Pounds 10m next year, giving a prospective p/e
of 13.8, would not seem ambitious.
</TEXT>
