FT  18 SEP 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Prospect of free trade in
coffee between Mexico and Canada
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of free trade in coffee between Mexico, the fourth largest
producer, and Canada, which imports around 2.3m bags a year, has further
muddied the waters of next week's ICO negotiations, writes David Blackwell.
The agreement between the two countries appears to be enshrined in an annex
to the North American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta). Mr Lawrence Eagles,
analyst with GNI, the London futures broker, pointed out yesterday that even
if consuming countries operated a penalty process for coffee outside a quota
system, Mexico would be able to export its full quota to any ICO consumer
and send the rest to Canada, which is not in the ICO.
