   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DELTA Air Lines, one of the big US carriers which is strongly opposing
British Airways' plan to invest Dollars 750m for a large minority stake in
USAir, yesterday called on the US Department of Transportation to hold
public proceedings to consider the issues involved.
The DoT, which must approve the deal, has not said how it plans to proceed -
in particular, whether it will hold public hearings on the matter. Earlier
this week, Mr Andrew Card, the transportation secretary, acknowledged that
there was intense interest in the proposed transaction and its implications
for future aviation policy, with the department receiving thousands of
letters on the subject.
Although BA would only have a minority interest in USAir, the large US
airlines claim that the deal is structured to give the UK airline effective
control over key areas of USAir's business. They claim that BA is thus
gaining access to the US domestic market, while formal bilateral aviation
agreements between the US and the UK severely restrict their access to the
UK.
This week, Mr Card indicated that the bilateral arrangements would be
'relevant' to his department decision on whether to approve the BA-USAir
deal, although he denied any 'formal' linkage between the two issues.
America West Airlines has formally received the funding from its Dollars 53m
debtor-in-possession financing package, Reuters reports from New York.
The company announced a new 10-member board of directors which provides GPA,
one of the financing participants, with two seats.
