<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / International Bonds: Swiss safe haven draws another issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE safe haven attraction of the Swiss currency during the current
turbulence in the European Monetary System prompted another borrower to tap
the Euro-Swiss franc bond market yesterday.
Bankers said the Electricite de France SFr100m offering was aggressively
priced for an issue with a 6 5/8 per cent coupon at 102, to yield 6.413 per
cent, but that this was not surprising since the French utility is a
top-quality borrower. What was more unusual was the 15-year duration of the
bond.
The issue was being quoted at about 2 1/2 points below its issue price,
yielding 6.65 per cent in late afternoon trading, just inside the lead
manager's fees. Some bankers also thought that the coupon was very low at 6
5/8 per cent, even though coupons have fallen from the 7 1/4 per cent on
Swiss Franc bond issues earlier in the week.
Lead managers UBS said switching by investors from the short end to the long
end of the Euro-Swiss franc bond market made this the ideal time to launch a
bond with a long maturity. The bank added that it was having no problems in
placing the bond.
Elsewhere, joint lead manager JP Morgan Securities announced that the
pricing of Kingdom of Spain's Dollars 1.5bn seven-year Eurobond, launched on
Wednesday, had been deferred until next Tuesday. The market was not unduly
surprised by the decision, following the failure to attract investor
interest in the light of upheaval in European financial markets.
The credit rating of Imperial Chemical Industries, the UK group, was cut by
two notches by Moody's Investor Service yesterday in reaction to its planned
demerger.
ICI's rating tumbled from Aa3 to A2, affecting around Dollars 3bn of debt
outstanding. The decision reflected Moody's belief that the planned demerger
of the group's biosciences business would proceed, leading to a significant
shift in the group's risk profile at a difficult time for the basic chemical
industry.
</TEXT>
