FT  18 SEP 92 / International Capital Markets: Malaysia agrees futures
market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MALAYSIA'S Ministry of Finance has given the go-ahead for the establishment
of a Kuala Lumpur Options and Financial Futures Exchange (Kloffe).
A consortium of private firms will run the new exchange. Those involved are
believed to have strong political connections. They are the New Straits
Times newspaper group; Renong, an industrial conglomerate; and two
securities firms, Rashid Hussain Bhd and Zalik Securities.
The consortium had been involved in a tussle with the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) and the Kuala Lumpur Commodity Exchange (KLCE) for operation
of the new exchange. The KLSE and KLCE were each offered a 20 per cent
equity participation in Kloffe by its future operators, but both bodies
declined.
