<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Data ignored as Dow focuses
on Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCKS moved narrowly with no clear trend yesterday and activity was
subdued as Wall Street remained focused on events in Europe, writes Karen
Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was finally 3.51 off at 3,315.70, after
showing a gain of some six points at midday. NYSE turnover was
unexceptional, at less than 190m shares, with falls leading rises by 940 to
785. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was just 0.01 up at 419.93 and the Nasdaq
composite put on 1.93 to 587.82.
The Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia reported that its index of business
activity in the area grew to 14.7 in September from August's 12.6, implying
slow but steady expansion in the manufacturing sector. Initial unemployment
claims for the week ended September 5 were up 6,000 to 400,000. There was
little market reaction to the domestic economic news, as attention remained
riveted on European money markets.
GTE, the biggest US local telephone company, led NYSE trading. The stock
firmed Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 33 after the company announced that it had
priced a 30m common stock offering at Dollars 32 7/8 a share. GTE has about
895m shares outstanding.
International Business Machines edged Dollars  7/8 higher to Dollars 83 3/4
, after losing Dollars 2 5/8 on Wednesday when analysts lowered their
ratings on the stock and reduced earnings forecasts following news that
Amdahl, another big mainframe computer maker, expected a third-quarter loss.
Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing declined Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 101 3/4
after the company warned that its 1992 earnings could fall at the low end of
analysts' estimates, depending on the economy. Analysts had predicted 1992
earnings of about Dollars 5.70 to Dollars 5.80 a share, after a 1991 figure
of Dollars 5.26.
United Technologies, the aero-engines to motor components group, tumbled
Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 51 3/8 on reports that its third-quarter results
would fall short of expectations.
Boeing eased Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 35 3/8 after the company reached an
agreement in principle with GPA Group, the aircraft leasing concern, to
defer delivery of up to 154 aircraft worth Dollars 5bn for up to three
years.
National Westminster's American Depositary Shares rose Dollars 2 1/2 to
Dollars 38 after the UK bank cut its base lending rate to 10 per cent from
12 per cent, bringing it back to its Wednesday morning level.
Constar International soared Dollars 7 7/8 to Dollars 32 1/4 after agreeing
to be acquired by Crown Cork &amp; Seal for Dollars 32 1/2 a share. Crown Cork
slipped Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 36 1/8 .
In Nasdaq trading, Apple Computer lost Dollars 1 to Dollars 46 after an
analyst at Donaldson Luf-kin &amp; Jenrette downgraded his rating on the stock
from 'neutral' to 'unattractive'. Canada
A FIRMER Canadian dollar eased currency worries, but Toronto stocks ended
lower as participants remained cautious. The French Maastricht vote on
Sunday, the triple-witching expiry and concern about European currencies
pressured the market.
The TSE 300 index lost 7.7 at 3,446.1 and falls outpaced advances by 319 to
240 after volume of 31.3m shares.
</TEXT>
