<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / UK Company News: APV declines 17% to Pounds 12m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APV, the food manufacturing equipment maker, blamed the lack of even a
modest economic recovery for a 17 per cent fall in profits for the first
half of 1992.
The return on sales margin slipped from 5.1 to 3.8 per cent.
The pre-tax decline to Pounds 12m (Pounds 14.5m) was struck on turnover up 8
per cent at Pounds 437m (Pounds 402.9m).
A fall in other operating income to Pounds 1.7m (Pounds 4.3m) contributed to
the near-20 per cent slide to Pounds 16.5m (Pounds 20.5m) in operating
profits.
APV said that demand had fallen in its dry food side, with sales down 10 per
cent at Pounds 127.8m and profits tumbling to Pounds 1.4m (Pounds 5.6m).
Mr Clive Strowger, who became chief executive in July after the early
retirement of Mr Fred Smith at the end of 1991, said that the French bakery
operations had suffered particularly from a lack of orders and a downturn in
profit.
Also the 'adverse' economic climate led to 'traditional customers deferring
capital investment programmes'.
With competition growing, net margins shrank from 3.9 to 1.1 per cent in the
division.
However, Sir Peter Cazalet, chairman, asserted: 'APV will undertake no
meaningful work at less than cost.'
By contrast, the liquid food division, fuelled by growth in continental
Europe and Asia, lifted profits from Pounds 10.5m to Pounds 11.3m on
turnover up almost 20 per cent at Pounds 247.3m (Pounds 206.9m). Margins
slipped from 5.1 to 4.6 per cent - the company said there was a 'shortfall
in high margin orders'.
In the 'hotch-potch' group of companies, of which Vent-Axia, the UK
ventilation fan maker, is 'the largest and the best', according to Mr
Strowger, profits eased to Pounds 3.8m (Pounds 4.4m) on turnover ahead at
Pounds 61.9m (Pounds 54m).
Earnings per share emerged at 2.8p (3.3p) net and 3.5p (3.7p) on a nil
distribution basis.
The interim dividend is unchanged at 2p.
COMMENT
Leaderless for the first half, APV now has Mr Strowger at the helm, and it
needs him to sort out the margins problem. Mr Smith tended to acquire
companies and then let them get on with running themselves. It is to be
hoped that the new chief executive will identify the over-complexity of the
group as a fundamental problem - it has 40 companies with 130 operations.
Stronger central controls are needed to take strategic planning, product
development and marketing by the scruff of the neck and Mr Strowger has his
work cut out. The dull results will remain so, though the 'disappointing'
order intake since June is a worry for a company with high operational
margins. Forecast full-year pre-tax profits of about Pounds 30m give a
multiple between 12 and 13. There is no great pressure on the dividend,
though things will drift until Mr Strowger has made his presence felt.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
