<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Interest cut helps Davis Service rise to
Pounds 8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DAVIS SERVICE Group, which has now all but severed its links with
motor-related activities, lifted pre-tax profits from Pounds 7.06m to Pounds
8.03m in the six months to June 30.
In July 1991 it sold three of its four motor dealerships for Pounds 6.69m to
a management buy-out and in early April this year disposed of its Godfrey
Davis (Contract Hire) business to NWS Bank, a subsidiary of the Bank of
Scotland, for Pounds 5.75m.
Pre-tax profits of the continuing businesses grew to Pounds 8.22m (Pounds
6.65m).
Mr George Boyle, finance director, said that contract hire carried a large
amount of 'back-to-back' borrowings. As a result of the sale, borrowings
were sharply cut to Pounds 8.3m at the end of June. At the beginning of the
half year they had stood at Pounds 77.8m. The only outstanding motor-related
activity is the dealership in St Albans.
Interest payable for the contract hire side totalled Pounds 2.75m in the
half, leaving group interest charges at Pounds 2.53m (Pounds 5.83m). This in
turn offset the fall in overall operating profits to Pounds 10.6m (Pounds
12.9m), though for continuing businesses there was a rise to Pounds 8.22m
(Pounds 7.68m).
Group turnover fell to Pounds 124.7m (Pounds 155m), but for continuing
activities, it rose almost 6 per cent to Pounds 112.2m.
By division, the textile maintenance side, which accounts for about 55 per
cent of the group, was hit by the effects of the recession on the hotel
industry in the Sunlight Textile Services segment, and by employers
controlling costs in Sunlight Workwear Services.
In site services - about 22 per cent of the group - improved demand from
local authorities for temporary classrooms offset falls in the construction
sector, which accounts for 40 per cent of the division.
Government policies of compulsory tendering and 'contracting out' helped
ensure a good performance in support services, which provides cleaning and
maintenance staff.
Earnings grew to 6.39p (5.61p) per share and the interim dividend is
maintained at 2.73p.
</TEXT>
