<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Protection plea for EC workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS should not suffer severe loss of rights to future occupational
pension benefits when they move jobs within the European Community,
according to a UK government draft proposal.
It is estimated that about 3m EC nationals work in other EC countries,
mainly in skilled manual, professional or managerial jobs. Labour mobility
is a principle aim of the European Community.
Watsons Europe, the actuarial firm, estimates that about 150,000 managers
are adversely affected by the lack of harmonisation in EC pensions. Some
workers are able to negotiate compensation for loss of pension rights with
their new employers.
The government believes the single European market, due to be completed by
December 31 1992, might mean many more workers moving between jobs in
different EC countries. Many migrants have to freeze occupational pensions
in one country and start a new one in the state to which they move.
Efforts to harmonise occupational pension schemes were scuppered last year
by the EC because pensions are linked to taxation and therefore affect the
sovereignty of member states' taxation policies.
The UK government intends to use its presidency of the council of ministers
to make progress on the issue. It hopes to reach an agreement in time for a
meeting of EC social affairs ministers in Edinburgh in December.
EC workers enjoy greater protection over state pension benefits. A British
worker who retires in France must be paid a proportionate amount of his or
her state pension from the country of origin, plus a proportionate amount of
that of the host country, depending on length of residence.
A consultation paper, published by the social security department, calls on
the EC to protect the future occupational benefits of these workers. The
paper includes the draft resolution for consideration by other EC member
states.
The deadline for comments on the Social Security Department's consultation
document is September 25 1992.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
