<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Dealing with a matter of trust: Norma Cohen meets the man
with the task of reforming pension law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Roy Goode, chairman of the government's independent Pension Law
Review Committee, makes little secret of the fact that he has chosen the
most contentious issue in the industry - and most commercially sensitive -
as his committee's central theme.
'There are rights of scheme members and there are expectations which are not
necessarily rights,' he said. 'Some of those expectations are reasonable and
some are not. The question is how far pension expectations need to be taken
into account by trustees.'
The conflict arises, he says, when employers make entitlement to benefits
vague to avoid locking themselves into commitments they may not be able to
afford, while employees make contributions in the belief that specific
benefits will be forthcoming in all circumstances.
'We are asking whether there are some scheme rules which are capable of
being exercised so unfairly that they should only be exercised with a
court's permission. And are there some which should be banned altogether?'
Within that framework lie matters of great commercial consequence, both for
scheme members who receive benefits and for corporate sponsors who, more or
less, underwrite them. 'You have to decide who owns the scheme before you
can decide on whose behalf you are protecting it,' he said.
Professor Goode will only smile when the commercial consequences of his
report are mentioned and says he has come to the matter with no particular
point of view. 'I have an open mind - but not a vacant one,' he said.
However, he acknowledges that he is likely to come under considerable
pressure from plan sponsors and their advisers to write a report with their
commercial interests in mind.
Already, the lobbying appears to have begun. Yesterday the pension fund
trade association, the National Association of Pension Funds, formally
offered its members expertise to help the committee, while actuarial
consultants R. Watsons said it would be encouraging its clients to respond
as well.
The committee has its roots in the unprecedented theft of more than Pounds
400m from pension schemes controlled by the late Robert Maxwell. But its
remit has been drawn to encompass what has emerged as the central issue in
the industry - ownership.
Revelations of mismanagement or misuse of surpluses have outraged pension
scheme members, sometimes with reason, sometimes not. But, in all, it has
created political pressure for pension fund reform as never before.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
