<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Policies 'promote business start-ups'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOTH THE UK and Germany have experienced substantial growth in
self-employment but the increase has been most dynamic in the UK, according
to a report from the Anglo-German Foundation for the Study of Industrial
Society, a charitable group.
In its report, the group, which seeks to promote closer understanding
between the UK and Germany, compares the phenomenon of self-employment in
both countries and examines common characteristics and differences.
The report says the UK economic and policy climate promotes start-ups, while
that in Germany favours maintaining those already self-employed.
Policymakers need to understand the implications of self-employment for the
labour market, it says.
Self-Employment in the UK and Germany. Anglo-German Foundation, 15 Albion
Close, Parkstone, Poole, Dorset BH12 3LL. Pounds 5.
