<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Output standstill hits hopes for recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES that British industry might be recovering from the recession were
dampened yesterday by news that manufacturing output was unchanged in July.
Official figures showed that the output of manufactured goods in the three
months to the end of July was flat compared with the previous three months
and 0.9 per cent lower than the same period a year ago. In July, the level
of output was the same as in June.
The figures suggested that a small rise in manufacturing production in the
first half of the year - which led some economists to suggest that
manufacturing industry had seen the worst of the recession - petered out
during the summer.
Manufacturing output rose 0.3 per cent in the first quarter of this year and
0.5 per cent in the second quarter after six consecutive quarters of falling
production.
Overall industrial production, which includes oil and gas output, grew 1 per
cent in July. That was due to a sharp increase in energy production.
The Central Statistical Office figures showed that output for most sectors
of manufacturing fell slightly or was flat during the three months to the
end of July. Food, drink and tobacco output grew by 1 per cent compared with
the previous three months, while output of the minerals, engineering,
textiles and clothing sectors was almost unchanged.
</TEXT>
