FT  18 SEP 92 / Fewer on state training projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of people on government training and employment programmes has
fallen 12.3 per cent since the spring of last year, refuting the widely-held
view that the unemployment figures are being substantially depressed by such
schemes.
The figure comes from the Department of Employment's Labour Force Survey,
which was yesterday published on a quarterly basis for the first time,
instead of annually.
The main reason for fall in the number of people on government schemes is
demographic - with fewer young people in the population going on to Youth
Training, the scheme for 16-18 year olds.
The government will take some cheer from the figure showing that 3m people
were receiving job-related training in spring this year, a rise of 66 per
cent compared with spring 1984 and a fall of only 100,000 or 4 per cent
compared with spring last year.
