<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Fudge and mudge alive and kicking: Alison Smith watches the
party's internal struggle for credibility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE bird that represents the Liberal Democrats has this week in Harrogate
been allowed out of its pre-election cage to fly freely around the
conference hall.
It will be back on its perch before the next election, but made the most of
its freedom at this gathering.
Had the conference been immediately before an election, the discussion of
prostitution would have been stifled; a wider range of speakers would have
been paraded in front of the cameras; and the man who urged: 'Let us go
forward as trendsetters' would surely have been dissuaded from wearing a
cosy, patterned cardigan as he did so.
There was a change in Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, too. For him a
pre-election conference would have been one long photo-opportunity, and he
would not have made the slip of an unduly sharp tone in response to Mr David
Alton's impending departure from the party over its policy on abortion.
That issue was a classic example of the party grassroots seizing its chance
to debate subjects which, however important, are peripheral to mainstream
politics.
At times this has led to self-parody: discussing cruelty to animals and
holding nine separate votes while the UK economy goes through its most
turbulent 24 hours in recent years is no way to solve the party's
credibility problem.
The activists remain unmoved by the evident irritation of some of the
party's MPs at such antics.
The document prepared by the policy committee and hailed by Mr Ashdown as
charting the way forward to the next election manifesto, escaped the
ignominy of being sent back to the drawing board by just 13 votes, and may
be unrecognisable when it next sees the light of day.
The conference also threw out policy proposals to bring franchising of
services and stations to British Rail; and heavily qualified the party
managers' commitment to the market while underlining the party's commitment
to full employment.
It was not all bad news for the leadership, however. One new feature was the
co-operation between the parliamentary party and the Association of Liberal
Democrat Councillors (ALDC) to ensure that Wednesday's strategy debate did
not end in a debacle.
The blandly worded motion's acceptance of dialogue outside the party -
although not the promotion of such dialogue - together with comforting
clauses about the commitment to community politics owed much to a proposal
from the ALDC. It seemed a far cry from the call that went out from the SDP
to end the 'fudge and mudge' of British politics.
The alliance with the ALDC is worth a great deal to the leadership,
especially as only 20 members of the party are in the House of Commons.
While the 3,500 Liberal Democrat councillors very rarely make national
headlines, they are, some MPs believe, at least as influential within the
party as their representatives at Westminster.
The deal between the two groups got the party through the conference,
although failed to hide the divide between those who believe co-operation
with Labour is needed, and those who believe it is the last thing that is
needed.
Liberal Democrat activists can seem given to idealism rather than realism,
but it was Ms Clare Brooks, a veteran Liberal activist and councillor, who
came the closest to summing up accurately the position on dialogue and
deals.
'At the end of the day, the parliamentary party will do whatever they want
to do,' she said.
They will do so when they know what it is. At present, the party that prides
itself on facing up to the difficult questions confronting the UK seems not
to have faced up to its own future.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
