<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Sterling and the UK Economy: The true cost to Britain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE true cost to Britain of its vain battle this week to defend the pound
emerged yesterday at about Pounds 750m, Peter Marsh writes. That is the
estimate of the amount by which the pounds that the Bank of England bought
for D-Marks in its intervention operations on Wednesday dropped in value
between the start of trading on that day and the close in London last night.
In a few hectic hours on Wednesday, the Bank bought sterling worth an
estimated Pounds 15bn for D-Marks from its foreign currency reserves. The
operations consumed a large chunk of Britain's Dollars 44bn fund of
reserves, as well as perhaps a third of the special Pounds 7bn foreign
currency loan which the Treasury arranged earlier this month as a 'war
chest' to defend sterling.
Yesterday's estimate of about Pounds 15bn in intervention by the Bank - the
Bundesbank and the Bank of France also bought sterling worth perhaps a
further Pounds 5bn - is an increase on the earlier estimate of Pounds 9bn.
The huge intervention effort on Wednesday is thought to be the biggest
action of this kind by a central bank to defend a currency.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
