<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Sterling and the UK Economy: Fund managers try to cut risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS STERLING sank further yesterday, foreign exchange dealers were not the
only professionals active in the market. Fund managers and corporate
treasurers with exposure to sterling have had a busy couple of days.
'It was a case of trying to minimise the risk in a portfolio,' said Mr
Terence Prideaux of Kemper Investment Management, a US investment house.
'Given the size of the currency flows, any prudent investment manager would
have had to explore the question of currency exposure.'
Another fund manager said: 'You knew, as soon as 15 per cent interest rates
were announced, that it wasn't sustainable.'
Dealers reported activity from a wide range of fund managers, particularly
Swiss and US. While some fund managers moved assets between markets, others
tried to hedge currency exposure within their existing portfolios.
'The main focus was hedging currencies against the D-Mark,' said Mr Axel
Benkner of DWS, the German fund management group.
Corporate treasurers, while still assessing the long-term effects of recent
events on their businesses, were also active in moving against potential
short-term exposure.
'There has been a fair amount of activity' among corporate treasurers, said
Mr Tony Rice, group treasurer at British Aerospace. 'Those of us with dollar
exposure have had to sit on our hands for a while.'
Even in the spot foreign exchange market - the world's most liquid market -
trading became difficult as the margin between buy and sell prices on the
dollar-sterling rate, normally 3-10 basis points, hit 50 basis points.
Some treasurers decided that discretion was the better part of valour. 'We
were reluctant to deal in a disorderly market,' said one corporate treasurer
at a UK company.
The recent level of volatility pushed prices up, making it uneconomical to
hedge using options. Instead, activity has been concentrated in the forward
foreign exchange market and even in the spot market, contributing to the
pressure on the pound.
In spite of tumultuous market conditions, foreign exchange traders found
themselves with a one-way bet as the Bank of England proved an unlimited
buyer of sterling throughout the day.
As the Bank intervened in the market, offering to buy sterling in minimum
amounts of Pounds 30m - compared with a normal market size of Pounds
5m-Pounds 10m - it found banks and corporate treasurers willing to sell.
'Every bank around the world had taken a position against sterling,' one
broker said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
