<DATE>920918
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Major strives to salvage policy: FT-SE jumps 105 points as
base rates are cut to 10 per cent and sterling sinks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday sought to salvage the government's economic strategy
from the wreckage of devaluation by insisting that sterling would eventually
rejoin the exchange rate mechanism.
But senior ministers were forced to admit that it might be months before
sterling was again tied to the D-Mark as it continued to sink in the
currency markets. Meanwhile, base rates were cut to 10 per cent and the
stock market soared.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, insisted the defeat of inflation would
remain at the core of his policy. However, ministerial colleagues said the
government could not now avoid a fundamental reappraisal of its overall
economic strategy.
Mr Major also faced the threat of revolt by Tory MPs over his approach to
Europe and the economy, with a growing number arguing that he should abandon
the ERM entirely in favour of a rapid cut in interest rates to 'kick-start'
economic recovery.
Mr Lamont, who was given a vote of confidence at an emergency cabinet
meeting, flatly rejected suggestions that he should resign. He said: 'I am
not going to resign. I have been operating the policy of the whole
government, and I know that I have the support of the prime minister and the
full support of my cabinet colleagues.' In his first formal television
interviews since the crisis erupted, Mr Lamont said: 'What we faced
yesterday - and in the last couple of weeks - has been a wholly exceptional
set of circumstances, the like of which haven't been seen for 20 years or
more.
'It affected not just this country but Italy, which has also had to leave
the exchange rate mechanism, and Spain, which has had to devalue its
currency as well. What I did yesterday was simple commonsense in the face of
a whirlwind.'
Mr Lamont denied there had been a devaluation of the pound. He told ITN: 'We
have not resorted to devaluation. The pound is now currently floating and we
will have to see what level it finds.'
The damage-limitation exercise did not dispel widespread doubts at
Westminster over the chancellor's long-term future. Some of his colleagues
believe his authority has been fatally undermined.
Cabinet ministers said that the political row over the Bundesbank's role in
causing the sterling crisis would delay attempts by the government to ratify
the Maastricht treaty even if it was approved by the French electorate on
Sunday.
It is now thought that detailed debate on the legislation will have to be
delayed until after the Edinburgh summit in December.
As the Bank of England reversed the 2-point rise in base rates announced as
part of its vain efforts on Wednesday, the pound slid more than 13 pfennigs
below its previous ERM floor to close in London at DM2.6400.
But the reversal of Wednesday's sharp rise in interest rates, and
expectations of further rate cuts gave share prices their biggest boost
since the Conservative party's election victory in April.
The FT-SE 100 share index closed up 105.6 at 2,483.9 in one of the most
heavily traded sessions on record. Equity dealers sensed that sterling's
effective devaluation and suspension from the ERM could signal a shift in UK
government policies in the direction of lower interest rates.
Mr Lamont, who appeared in surprisingly resilient mood after the drama of
Wednesday's devaluation, indicated that he wanted to make a number of
assessments before deciding when and at what rate to take the pound back
into the ERM.
The most immediate would be the pattern of exchange after the results of the
French referendum. But the chancellor also wants a thorough examination by
the European Community of the effectiveness of co-operation between
governments and central banks within the ERM.
Such a debate would focus inevitably on the obligations of the Bundesbank in
helping to defend the weaker currencies.
Mr Lamont's next concern is to get confirmation that German interest rates -
at the root of sterling's problems in the ERM - are set firmly on a downward
path before fixing a new rate for the pound against the D-Mark.
That suggests the Treasury believes there may be scope for further small
cuts in British interest rates over the next few months if the inflation
rate continues to fall at the present rate.
In spite of Mr Lamont's devaluation denial, there was little conviction
behind Downing Street's suggestion that it was possible that sterling could
rise significantly before it was taken back into the ERM.
Mr Major's aides were keen to stress that every member of the cabinet had
endorsed at yesterday's meeting the decision to rejoin eventually.
Some ministers were also raising the question of whether Mr Major should
re-examine the option of granting statutory independence to the Bank of
England - an idea favoured by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary. The aim would be to restore credibility to the government's
anti-inflation strategy. But colleagues said that after his experience in
recent days with the Bundesbank, Mr Lamont was disinclined to consider it as
an immediate option.
Seizing on the cabinet's attempt to rally to Mr Lamont, Labour gave notice
that it would target Mr Major as chief culprit for the sterling crisis in
next Thursday's Commons debate.
While Mr John Smith, the party leader, claimed that the chaotic events
revealed 'muddle and confusion' at the heart of Mr Major's government, Mr
Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, quoting from Mr Major's speech made
less than a week ago that ruled out devaluation, said: 'It is time for the
prime minister to explain in full in a statement to the British people what
the government policy for the economy now is.'
