<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / BNL case reversal may embarrass Bush
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATLANTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US court case over Dollars 5bn of illegal Iraqi loans made by the
Atlanta branch of Italy's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL) took an
unexpected turn yesterday when lawyers for the former branch manager of BNL
Atlanta said he wished to withdraw his guilty plea and face a full-scale
trial instead.
The court, which was supposed to be considering a prison sentence for Mr
Christopher Drogoul, the former BNL manager, was told that he had been
pressed by government prosecutors to support their theory that he was the
sole orchestrator of the Iraqi loans scandal.
More than Dollars 2bn of the BNL loans helped to finance Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein's nuclear, chemical and ballistic weapons projects.
The reason for changing Mr Drogoul's plea from guilty to innocent, it was
argued, was fresh evidence indicating that he had acted with the approval of
BNL's management in Rome and with the knowledge of the US government.
BNL has denied that it was aware of the Iraqi loans, and the US prosecutors
have argued that Mr Drogoul defrauded BNL. But defence lawyers have cited
evidence to the contrary, including a 1991 CIA report, disclosed in the US
Congress this week, which states that BNL officials in Rome knew of the
Iraqi loans and even signed some of them.
Judge Marvin Shoob, who has already said he does not believe Mr Drogoul
acted alone, announced he would rule on the plea motion next Tuesday in
Atlanta.
The Bush administration could face serious embarrassment if the judge were
to decide to order a full BNL trial.
Federal prosecutors said they were inclined to oppose the request and the
judge, after first saying he was unlikely to grant the motion, then said:
'Candidly I don't know what I am going to do. The defence may have good
reasons for changing the plea.'
Mr Bobby Lee Cook, the prominent Georgia lawyer defending Mr Drogoul, told
the FT he would argue that the BNL manager was carrying out the policies of
BNL, with acquiescence and permission from BNL in Rome. 'Mr Drogoul was also
facilitating the well-known policy of the American government in supplying
arms, technology and other materiel to Iraq. He believed that the government
of the United States knew precisely what was happening and did not object
because it was consonant with their policy at that time,' the lawyer said.
In court yesterday, Mr Cook named a former US intelligence agent as one of
the key intermediaries in the BNL Atlanta Iraqi loan programme.
'It is obvious from this hearing that the government has not been forthright
or honest,' Mr Cook claimed. 'The government would have the court and the
public believe this entire affair was designed and orchestrated by a young
branch manager, without any knowledge or approval from Rome. That position
offends logic and also turns the facts upside-down.
'It is an effort on behalf of the administration to rewrite and to
reconstitute history, and to hide and suppress from the court and from the
people the devastating and catastrophic blunders that our government made in
arming and supporting Saddam Hussein,' Mr Cook said.
</TEXT>
