<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Phone services told to allow more competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Federal Communications Commission has ruled that telephone companies
must allow competitors greater access to public telephone networks. The
decision paves the way for competition in the Dollars 90bn US regional
telephone service market.
'A monopoly assures the quiet life. I think the quiet life has ended,' said
Mr Alfred Sikes, FCC chairman. Its action yesterday represented 'a historic
step' in opening 'one of the last monopoly reserves' in the
telecommunications industry.
'This decision finally gives customers the ability to select the company
that provides their local (telephone) access service,' said Mr Royce
Holland, president of Metropolitan Fiber Systems, a company that has been
seeking access to the local telephone service market.
The FCC, in a series of unanimous decisions, is to allow companies that
operate private networks to connect their networks to local telephone
networks and has proposed letting such connections take public telephone
services.
The regulator also decided to change eventually the way local telephone
companies price the use of their networks by long-distance telephone service
providers.
Prices will not change for the next 12 months, however, until a plan has
been designed to link access charges to the volume of telephone traffic
provided by a long-distance telephone company.
'With expanded competition, the FCC now should move quickly to reduce
regulation of local exchange companies. That would represent further
progress toward a fully competitive marketplace and be beneficial to
consumers,' said Ameritech, the parent company of telephone companies in the
Great Lakes region.
</TEXT>
