<PROFILE>_AN-CIRBKAHVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920918
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Sterling and the UK Economy: Lamont denies shift in policy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont last night gave the following interview to BBC television
news:
Interviewer: It was said again and again that the pound would not be
devalued and the government would take whatever measures are necessary to
prevent that. Those statements turned out not to be true. How can anybody
rely on your word?
Mr Lamont: 'I have not sought a devaluation, nor I think did the Italian
prime minister, nor the Spanish finance minister, all of whom found
themselves overwhelmed by the extraordinary events of the last couple of
weeks, the like of which we haven't seen for 20 or 30 years.
'It has been a very exceptional set of circumstances. The French referendum
has created extraordinary strains within the exchange rate mechanism and
this has posed enormous problems, not just for us, but for many other
countries.
'I don't suppose the Swedish finance minister found it very easy putting up
interest rates to some 500 per cent over-night.
'That is the sort of extraordinary circumstance that we have been living
through. What I did was simple common sense. The decision I made was an
unavoidable one.'
That justified you in being unable to live up to your word?
'I believe the decision that I made was the correct one, since I have not
sought a devaluation, I did not seek to leave the exchange rate mechanism,
but we were overwhelmed by these wholly exceptional circumstances.'
How was it that the centrepiece as you described it of the government's
whole economic strategy for the next many years could be destroyed in one
day?
'Well, what we have done is to suspend our membership and I have made it
clear that we intend to resume our membership when circumstances allow. But
our policy is a continuous one.
'Our policy is to get inflation down and there will be no let-up in that at
all. We have been dramatically successful in getting inflation down from
nearly 11 per cent to under 4 per cent in less than two years. It's been a
long, hard slog and I can assure you, having worked so hard to get this
country to be a country of low inflation, I am not going to chuck it away
just in a few weeks' time. I refuse to do that.'
But, chancellor, again, how did it happen that the centrepiece of membership
of the ERM was destroyed in one day?
'What happened was that we faced an extraordinary set of circumstances - a
huge speculative flow that was shifting because of the uncertainties caused
by the French referendum. Those were circumstances the like of which we
haven't seen for decades.'
And which you did not foresee?
'I did not foresee that we would be forced to take the decision that we had
to take.'
</TEXT>
