<DATE>920918
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 SEP 92 / Slow progress on the 'green' route: EC environment ministers
face a tough task after Rio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOMORROW'S meeting of European Community environment ministers at Gleneagles
in Scotland will show that progress on enforcing environmental rules remains
elusive, in spite of the UK's vigorous promises of action three months ago
when it took over the EC presidency.
The informal council meeting will be the first time all 12 environment
ministers have met since the Rio Earth Summit in June. It has been called
because of the summit's weighty legacy of administration.
Heading the agenda is the task of putting into practice the Rio resolutions
on reducing emissions of greenhouse gases and preserving biodiversity - the
distribution of the world's species.
The UK intends to ratify the climate-change convention - for which it needs
parliamentary approval - by 1993, but has given no date for biodiversity.
The Gleneagles meeting will also consider how to promote 'the greening of
all EC legislation'. That policy is expected to have the support of Mr Karel
van Miert, who took up a six-month appointment as EC environment
commissioner in June, and who is also the community's transport
commissioner.
DG11, the EC environmental council's policy development arm, has had little
influence with other Brussels directorates, and several large Mediterranean
projects have recently received EC money although they were then deemed to
be environmentally harmful.
Behind the scenes, members of the UK team are lobbying for Mr Miert to
remain commissioner after December - he has given a more encouraging
response to the UK position than his predecessor, Mr Carlo Ripa di Meana.
However, moves to enforce EC 'green' rules more vigorously - which Mr
Michael Howard, UK environment minister, announced would be a priority - are
making slow progress. Gleneagles will be told that representatives from
national enforcement agencies will have their first meeting in November, but
that falls short of the UK's original plan for a central 'inspectorate of
inspectorates'.
Nor does the repeal of some EC legislation on water standards at which Mr
Howard hinted in June, now look likely.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
