<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / Ashdown fillip on co-operation: The Liberal Democrats at
Harrogate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PADDY ASHDOWN, the party leader, was yesterday given an almost free hand
to develop co-operation with other parties. A motion expressing a belief in
working with anyone like-minded and in promoting campaigns on common causes
received strong support at the Liberal Democrat conference.
In his rallying speech to the conference this afternoon, Mr Ashdown is
expected to welcome yesterday's resolution as a good base from which to
proceed. Today's speech will also be used to launch Mr Ashdown's first
full-scale attack on Mr John Major's lack of leadership since the election.
Previously he has sometimes sounded as though he admires the prime minister.
In deliberately rejecting the idea of 'promoting' discussion, the agreement
reached yesterday is a dilution of what Mr Ashdown appeared to have in mind
in his speech in Chard, Somerset, soon after the general election. Then, in
a move which left many of his parliamentary colleagues unhappy, he called
for the Liberal Democrats to be the 'catalyst' for debate with people of
other parties and the politically uncommitted.
The party activists' deep-rooted suspicion of Labour was reflected in many
speeches, and in the cheers that greeted the rejection of an amendment
highlighting areas where members of the two parties agree.
Mr Simon Hughes, MP for Southwark and Bermondsey, argued that an earlier
proposal which referred to 'promoting a process of discussion' represented a
'begging-bowl approach'.
But Dr Jenny Tonge, the party's general election candidate in Richmond and
Barnes, warned delegates that, in order to defeat the Conservatives, some
Liberal Democrats would have to consider voting tactically for Labour as
some Labour supporters had done in Richmond and Barnes at the election.
Several speakers repeated warnings that it was the electorate's view of the
Liberal Democrats' as being close to Labour that had prevented them from
achieving greater success in the general election.
</TEXT>
