</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / International Company News: Bata to reopen shops in Poland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BATA, one of the world's largest shoe producers and retailers, is returning
to Poland with the intention of establishing a nationwide network of retail
sales outlets. The move follows the company's return last year to
Czechoslovakia, where it was founded in 1894.
Bata was nationalised by the Communist Czechoslovak government after the
second world war, but has opened 40 shops there this year and bought one
medium-sized shoe producer.
Bata is the first western 'high street' retailer to come to Poland, where
trade remains largely in the hands of small private companies catering for
the country's nearly 40m consumers.
The Bata Shoe Organisation, the holding company for the group, has its
headquarters in Toronto.
Bata will be operating in Poland through Compar Bata, its Italian
subsidiary, in a joint venture with Intercam, which is a privately-owned
Polish company.
Intercam, founded in 1988, is also involved in joint ventures with DHL, the
international freight forwarding group and Ogilvy Mather, the advertising
company.
Bata is planning to open some 30 shops in Poland over the next few years and
intends to purchase some stock from the country's depressed shoe industry.
The company had 300 shops in Poland before the second world war and owned
two factories on what is now Polish territory.
However, Mr Thomas G Bata, the company's managing director, says it will not
be applying for their restitution nor does he have any immediate plans for
the purchase of existing plants.
</TEXT>
