<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / Top bosses seek work consensus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ATTEMPT to create an industrial consensus based on the idea of
flexibility for employers and job security plus involvement for employees
was launched yesterday with the backing of several senior industrialists and
union leaders.
Sir Bryan Nicholson, chairman of the Post Office, Mr David Sainsbury, deputy
chairman of J. Sainsbury, and Sir John Harvey-Jones, former chairman of
Imperial Chemical Industries, were among supporters of the initiative
launched by the Involvement and Participation Association. It was also
backed by senior personnel directors at ICI and Unilever.
The main proposals, which have emerged from private discussions between
industrialists, union leaders and academics over the past two years,
include:
Making employment security the cornerstone of employment policy but linking
it with job flexibility.
Commitment to sharing success with the whole workforce.
Recognising employees' right to be informed, consulted and represented
whether they are in a union or not.
Sir Bryan acknowledged that employers and unions would have difficulty in
accepting parts of the document.
The employment security commitment is likely to be especially difficult for
employers, and some unions will find it difficult to give implicit support
for German-style works councils and other forms of employee participation,
which are seen as bypassing unions.
The association is asking for responses from companies, unions and other
groups.
Unemployment has risen more than 70 per cent in the past two years, more
than any other country in Europe, according to Ms Joyce Quin, a member of
Labour's employment team. The monthly unemployment figures today are
expected to show a 20,000-plus rise from the previous 2.75m, taking
unemployment near 9 per cent.
</TEXT>
