   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON needs a significant increase in its government-funded budgets for
training and business support if the capital is to lead Britain out of
recession, according to a report published yesterday by the capital's nine
Training and Enterprise Councils.
The Tecs said training of young people and unemployed adults in London had
been historically underfunded compared with other regions. Tecs required an
increase of between 40 per cent and 60 per cent, or an extra Pounds 45m to
Pounds 68m.
The report by Coopers and Lybrand, the management consultancy, is the first
big exercise in collaboration between Tecs to analyse and explore a regional
issue.
Its costings were dismissed by Mr Michael Forsyth, employment minister, who
said there were errors in the report.
Mr David Dickinson, chairman of London East Tec, said in response to the
minister's criticisms that the report was based on all the information that
was publicly available. He added that if the government disputed the figures
it should make its internal costings available.
