<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The programme listings should have a stock of logos saying 'OLD]', then when
all those familiar series return for the autumn season they could be given
accurate labels instead of 'NEW' claims. Among the well worn series
reappearing today are Taggart (9.00 ITV) with the glum little Scottish
detective played, as ever, by Mark McManus.
BBC1 brings back one of British television's earlier and most highly rated
examples of tabloid television, Crimewatch UK. Like Dickens' Fat Boy this
sets out to make our flesh creep with tales of 'orrible murder and then,
unlike the Fat Boy, grinningly instructs us not to have nightmares. That is
followed by another old series, Question Time (10.15). It is as well to have
some form of extra-parliamentary forum on television to discuss current
politics, but this programme has never been the same since Robin Day left.
BBC2's fascinating series The Climbers (8.00) ends with Chris Bonington
considering the modern phenomenon of superfast climbers who, in a few hours,
race to summits which once took days for large expeditions. Has
mountaineering turned into a stunt?
