<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / The ERM and Britain: Labour pins blame on ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR acted swiftly yesterday to pin the blame for the interest rate rises
firmly on the government's refusal to stimulate the economy.
Mr John Smith, who is at the Socialist International conference in Berlin,
said: 'Mr Major and his government have failed not just their country but
the whole (European) Community.'
The Labour leader highlighted the opposition's consistent demands, dating
from well before the April election, for tax incentives for industry and
other measures to stimulate growth.
He added that yesterday's events represented 'an almost total defeat' for
the government's economic strategy. 'This is the result of the failure to
invest, of the failure to pay attention to the real economy. It's the
fundamental weakness of the economy after 13 years of Conservative
government that is at the heart of the matter.'
In London Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, pressed home Labour's
attack, pointing out that Tory election propaganda had consistently promised
sustained recovery and lower interest rates.
Labour will make the prime minister, not Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor,
the principal target for attack when parliament is recalled next Thursday.
Senior party sources said: 'We are not going to accept that Norman Lamont
might be the ultimate fall guy. For it was the prime minister who could not
have been more categoric about staking his reputation on the value of the
pound.'
The Labour leadership must nonetheless tread warily, knowing that a number
of its senior spokesmen are critical of the opposition of Mr Smith and Mr
Brown to a devaluation strategy.
The party leadership will keep a tight rein on its internal dissidents ahead
of Sunday's French referendum. It will then have three days to devise a
coherent position on the ERM, sterling and the Maastricht treaty that will
command the maximum support across the party.
</TEXT>
