<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / The ERM and Britain: Counting cost of conviction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOW MR John Major must assess the cost of conviction. During 22 frequently
turbulent months in No 10 Downing Street, the prime minister has weathered
his share of crises, but yesterday's turmoil on financial markets confronts
him with the most serious test of his political career.
As the currency markets jeered his government, the official message was that
Mr Major remained determined to hold sterling at the rate at which he took
it into the Exchange Rate Mechanism two years ago.
The speculators were unimpressed. When the pound slid below its ERM floor,
the question asked in Whitehall - and left unanswered - was whether his
determination would be enough.
An emergency meeting of senior ministers called by Mr Major last night
intensified speculation that the government would be forced to admit that
sterling's position was no longer sustainable.
There was no such ambiguity in briefings from the prime minister's aides. Mr
Major was committed to the defeat of inflation, they said. In spite of
recent turbulence, he regarded the ERM as the framework to achieve that
objective. He would do 'whatever is necessary to defend the parity'.
But as Mr Major tied his government's future irrevocably to the fate of
sterling, criticism from the business community was matched by
recriminations from the Conservative back benches.
Some ministers were arguing privately that there had to be a point beyond
which even Mr Major could not take his commitment to sterling's DM2.95
central rate in the ERM. 'Will it be 25 per cent (base rates) by Friday?'
one asked.
For Tory Euro-sceptics, the threat that higher borrowing costs would drive
the economy from recession into slump is an ideal recruiting ground in the
campaign against the Maastricht treaty.
Even before yesterday's drama, the Euro-sceptics were promising that the
prime minister would receive a stormy reception at the party conference in
Brighton in two weeks. It was once supposed to be a celebration. Now they
are pledging open revolt.
A French Yes for Maastricht in Sunday's referendum would ease some tensions
on the financial markets but it would still foreshadow a bitter struggle
with the Tory rebels. There was acknowledgement in Whitehall yesterday that
even if the treaty was endorsed by the French, it would be some time before
interest rates fell again to 10 per cent.
With one or two MPs publicly calling for Mr Norman Lamont's resignation, the
possibility of a symbolic challenge to Mr Major's leadership can no longer
be dismissed as fantasy.
The Chancellor acknowledged the risk of a political backlash in the
statement that followed the first base rate rise. In an attempt to strike a
note of reassurance, he voiced hopes that the move would be short-lived. It
was a mistake. The markets took the comment as a sign of weakness.
There has been no sign of revolt in the senior ranks of the government. When
the absolute commitment to sterling's parity was underlined by Mr Lamont at
last week's cabinet meeting, no one voiced dissent.
As one senior minister said later, even the cabinet room is too public a
place to voice doubts about the chancellor's handling of the pound.
There was renewed speculation yesterday that if the government is defeated
by the markets Mr Lamont will have to leave the Treasury. Inevitably, the
parallel that was being drawn was with the resignation as chancellor of the
then Mr James Callaghan in 1967, when he was forced into devaluation.
This time it is not that simple. Mr Harold Wilson, then prime minister,
distanced himself from his chancellor's handling of the sterling crisis. Mr
Major has done the reverse.
The strategy now is to try to hold the line until Sunday, hoping that a Yes
vote will bring a return to sanity. Senior Downing Street officials pointed
out that even if Mr Major wanted to devalue - and he did not - Italy's
experience in the past few days demonstrated that that would not offer an
easy escape route.
The markets seemed disinclined to offer even that brief respite. There was a
real fear in Whitehall that the scale of speculation against the pound would
sweep away all the government's good intentions when the markets reopen
today.
There was also barely concealed fury at the Bundesbank's role. Two weeks
ago, Mr Lamont was winning plaudits for organising a co-ordinated EC assault
on the German central bank's refusal to cut interest rates. The view in
Downing Street now is that the Bundesbank has been wreaking its revenge with
persistent hints that it believes sterling should be devalued.
Mr Major's instinct is to tough it out. For him, the prize of victory
against the markets would be a credibility for his anti-inflation strategy
that has eluded every British post-war government.
It is an enormous gamble. The markets have been unimpressed by conviction
politics. If Mr Major wins against the odds, he will emerge as strong a
prime minister as any in recent history. But last night, speculation in
Whitehall was focused on the cost of losing.
</TEXT>
