<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / PSBR figure better than expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUBLIC-SECTOR finances deteriorated by less than expected last month,
although government tax receipts continued to be restrained by the
recession.
The public sector borrowing requirement in August was Pounds 2.9bn, more
than Pounds 500m lower than forecast. Privatisation proceeds in the month
were close to zero.
That brought the cumulative PSBR total since April - the beginning of the
financial year - to Pounds 14.3bn compared with Pounds 7.9bn in the same
period last year. Excluding privatisation proceeds, the cumulative total was
Pounds 17.8bn.
In the March Budget, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, forecast a PSBR of
Pounds 28bn, double the size of the previous year's deficit. However, with
the chances of an economic upturn this year looking increasingly remote, the
Treasury's forecast is likely to be exceeded as tax receipts fail to live up
to expectations and high unemployment keeps government spending high. The
latest view of forecasters is that the PSBR will reach Pounds 32bn this
financial year.
Last month's better-than-expected figure was helped by net repayments from
local authorities and public corporations.
</TEXT>
